he culture that migrants brought with them-including music, food, religion, and sports-and shows how these traditions were adapted to new circumstances. Working-class African Americans in Richmond used their cultural venues-especially the city's legendary blues clubs-as staging grounds from which to challenge the racial status quo, with a steadfast determination not to be "Jim Crowed" in the Golden State.As this important work shows, working-class African Americans often stood at the forefront of the struggle for equality and were linked to larger political, social, and cultural currents that transformed the nation in the postwar period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / West (AK, CA, CO, HI, ID, MT, NV, UT, WY).2bisacsh  aacademic.  aafrican american communities.  aafrican american.  aarchival.  abay area.  ablack communities.  acase study.  acommunity.  acultural history.  afactory workers.  aindustrial.  ajim crow.  amigration.  aminorities.  aminority.  amusic.  anewspaper.  aoral history.  apolitical.  apolitics.  arace issues.  arace.  aracism.  areligion.  aresearch.  asan francisco bay.  asan francisco.  ascholarly.  asmall town.  asocial history.  atraditional.  awater.  aworking class.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052022920440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520927124zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520927124423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520927124.jpg  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles